Title: Whisper of a Dance Forgotten
Author: <lj user="warwithheaven">
Overall Rating: R
Chapter Rating: G
Pairing: In future, HP/SS/DM
Length: Chapter One- 650 words  Total- 650 words
Summary: Harry returns 'home' after seven years and finds more than he bargained for.
Warnings: AU, threesome, torture, character death, almost all warnings pertain to future chapters.


Disclamer: Not mine, nor will it ever be mine. All belong to J.K. Rowling and whoever else has their hands in it.

This is the first thing I have ever posted, anywhere, so tell me what you think. I plan on it being about 25-30 chapters... and I have about ten written and it is about 26,000 words... but I have to go back and add some things to it and fix it. And I know the summary isn't much to go by, but I've never been really good at writing them. I hope you like it.

<lj-cut text="Prologue">

"Sir, do you have your ticket?"

Blinking, the young man turned in his seat towards the voice. "Excuse me?"

The woman sighed and asked gently, "Do you have your ticket?"

"Oh, yes." The young man reached for the bag that was on the ground by his feet and started to shuffle through numerous papers, muttering to himself all the while. "I know it is in here. Maybe..." He stuck his hand deep into the bag, deeper than the woman thought was possible, before he smiled and pulled his arm out the bag with his ticket clasped in his hand. "I knew I had it."

The woman smiled gently. "Of course." The young man turned back to look out the window of the train he was in while the woman checked over his ticket. The sky was clear, not a cloud in sight, and the sun shone almost too brightly for his liking. He tried to look for something interesting in the fields that they were passing, but all he could see where herds of sheep and cows and a few houses here in there. Overall it was a rather boring trip.

The lady that sat two rows behind him was asleep and snoring loudly, so loudly in fact that he fancied he could feel the vibrations of each of her snores. There was a tall skinning man that sat in the seat in front of him that kept tapping his pen as he read "How Not to Lose The Spice in Your Life" by R.P. Rynolds. And, at the front of his train car was a family of three, a wife, a husband, and a little girl that couldn't have been more than six years old. The girl kept on telling her mother that there was a monster in the toilet, while both of her parents tried to reassure her that there were no such things as monsters.

The young man smiled slightly. A boring trip indeed.

"Sir, your ticket." The woman said, holding out the ticket towards him.

"Thank you." He smiled politely. The woman nodded and went to wake the woman who was snoring so that she could see her ticket.

Alone, once more, or alone as one can be with other people around him, he closed his eyes. Sleep had escaped him for the past few nights and he could feel exhaustion creeping in on him.

He couldn't fall asleep though, not where other people could see him. Not so they could see him when he thrashed around and screamed from the dreams of blood, death, torture...

No, best not to think of that.

He opened his eyes. He couldn't fall asleep here. Who knows what might escape.

So, the young man turned his thoughts to other things, random things, like how warm it would be tomorrow or when the next eclipse would be. But these thoughts did not entertain him for long, just a few minuets until his mind wandered to what was about to occur.

After seven years he was returning to a place he thought he would never see again... or better yet never wanted to see again. He didn't know why he was going 'home'. He had only received an urgent message that stated 'We need you, now. -D.' Memories of times past flashed in his eyes. Memories of smiling faces, of joyous laughter, of painful tears, and of sweet decline.

Shaking his head, the young man pushed those thoughts from his mind.

'Stop thinking about it. You have a least two more hours of peace, of normalcy, don't get hasty and throw it away.' He thought as he pushed his hair behind his ears, revealing a faded scar across his forehead in the shape of a lightening bolt.

Harry Potter was returning home.

For better or for worse.

'I only wish I knew what was going on.' Harry thought before returning his attention to the bright and sunny day outside.

</lj-cut>

My name is Heven and I absolutly love Harry Potter! This will be a place where I post stories and recommendations and really just about anything. I have never posted a story... actually no one has read any of them... But anyway, I just wanted to have this up and running and maybe I'll get my first story up in a few days.

Thanks!

Heven
